equation_narrative.headline: Positive charge signal emerges late, K wins over R via MLP amplification
equation_narrative.story: Position 48 in ubiquitin sits in a charged surface context with 7 co-evolving positions and minimal structural contacts. Through L23, the model assembles a representation that fluctuates between polar (S, T, N) and small hydrophobic (A) character, reflecting the local sequence environment. The decisive shift occurs at L27-29 when positive charge prediction channels activate: K emerges at L29 (25.4%) and surges to 87.5% by L33, driven by highly specific MLP neurons (N29:1029 with 1.265 projection) and attention features (F33:6423 with 124.19 projection). R remains competitive through L31 (35.3%) but loses ground in the final layers as K-specific features dominate.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 show volatile representation character with frequent lead changes among polar and small residues. Only 2 structural contacts provide limited 3D context, while 7 co-evolving positions suggest functional coupling. Early attention features (F1:5480, F1:9146 at ~45 proj) encode local sequence context from the LIFAG[K]QLEDG motif. The logit lens fluctuates between S (22.6% at L1), Y (28.1% at L3), Q (22.9% at L7), and A (20.0% at L22), reflecting the model's assembly of a surface-exposed, polar-leaning representation rather than prediction attempts. By L23, the representation has not yet committed to charge character—Q holds 6.39%, K only 1.28%, and polar/small residues dominate the logit lens projection.
perception_phase.context_character: Surface-exposed position with polar/small residue character through L23. Minimal structural contacts (only 2) but strong co-evolutionary signal (7 positions) suggests functional constraint rather than packing requirement.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: only 2 residues within 8Å, providing minimal 3D packing constraints
Co-evolutionary signal: 7 coupled positions indicate functional importance, likely electrostatic or binding-related
Local sequence reading: L24 head 19 (2.567 proj, 94.5% local attention) reads immediate context from LIFAG and QLEDG flanking regions
Early features encode position character: F9:5728 (50.49 proj, attention) and F18:6632 (21.16 proj, attention) capture surface exposure and polar environment

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes at L27-29 when positive charge prediction channels activate. K emerges at L29 (25.4%) via N29:1029 (1.265 proj, K-specific neuron) and accelerates through L30-33 with massive MLP support (N31:4836 contributes 1.428 proj). R competes strongly, peaking at L31 (35.3%), but K-specific attention features in L32-33 (F33:6423 at 124.19 proj, F33:4166 at 119.77 proj) seal the victory. The final margin is decisive: 87.5% K vs 10.8% R.
decision_phase.transition: L23-25 marks the perception-to-decision boundary. At L23, no positive charge candidate exceeds 2.11% (R) or 1.28% (K), and the representation remains polar/small (T 14.7%, S, A). At L24, MLP neurons begin casting AA-specific votes (N24:4998 with 0.718 K-proj, 0.777 R-proj), and by L25, K reaches 9.8% as prediction channels activate. The shift from 'encoding surface polar context' to 'predicting specific positive charge' occurs precisely here.

candidates.narrative: K emerges late at L27-29 (from 1.28% at L23 to 25.4% at L29) and dominates the final layers. The decisive push comes from N29:1029 (1.265 proj, strongest K-specific neuron across all layers) and N31:4836 (1.428 proj). Final-layer attention features F33:6423 (124.19 proj) and F33:4166 (119.77 proj) provide massive amplification, driving K to 87.5%. The model correctly identifies this as a positively charged surface position requiring lysine's specific chemistry.

candidates.narrative: R tracks closely with K through L29 (20.5% vs 25.4%) and briefly leads at L28 (26.1%). It peaks at L31 (35.3%), supported by neurons like N28:4625 (0.936 R-proj, 0.418 K-proj) and N29:3922 (0.885 R-proj, 0.638 K-proj). However, R loses decisively in L31-33 as K-specific features dominate: R drops from 35.3% to 10.8% while K surges to 87.5%. The model distinguishes between the two positive charges, favoring K's specific functional role.

N29:3922 (0.885 R-proj) — R-favoring neuron at L29

candidates.narrative: Q dominates the logit lens through much of the perception phase (22.9% at L7, 14.7% at L9, 17.8% at L29), reflecting the polar character of the assembled representation and the adjacent Q at position 49. This is NOT the model predicting Q—it's the representation correlating with polar/amide chemistry as the model reads local context. Q peaks at L32 (25.0%) before collapsing to 1.4% as K-specific prediction channels override the polar signal. The early Q prominence reflects context assembly, not decision-making.

candidates.narrative: N peaks at L17 (18.5%), reflecting the polar/small character of the mid-layer representation. Features like F18:6632 (21.16 proj) encode surface-exposed polar context that projects toward N in the logit lens. This early prominence is an artifact of representation assembly—the model is encoding 'polar surface position' which happens to correlate with N, not predicting N. N fades rapidly after L17 (3.4% at L23, 0.09% final) as charge-specific features emerge.

turning_points.description: The representation character shifts from aromatic/polar (Y 28.1% at L3) to polar/amide (Q 22.9% at L7) to small polar (N 18.5% at L17, S/T oscillating). This reflects the model assembling surface-exposed polar context from local sequence and minimal structural contacts. Attention heads read the QLEDG downstream context, and features like F9:5728 (50.49 proj) encode the emerging polar character. The frequent lead changes (Y→Q→A→R→N→S) indicate the representation has not yet resolved the specific chemistry required.

The decisive shift from polar to positive charge occurs here. At L27, Q leads (22.0%) with K at only 11.9%. By L29, K jumps to 25.4% (overtaking R at 20.5%) driven by N29:1029 (1.265 K-proj) and N29:3922 (0.885 R-proj, 0.638 K-proj). MLP layer 29 contributes +4.08 total answer projection, the strongest positive push in the decision phase. This is where the model commits to positive charge and begins distinguishing K from R.

K surges from 25.4% to 87.5% while R collapses from 35.3% to 10.8%. L31 MLP contributes +3.21 proj via N31:4836 (1.428 K-proj). L32 attention delivers +5.4 proj (largest attention delta), driven by heads reading final context. L33 features F33:6423 (124.19 proj) and F33:4166 (119.77 proj) provide massive K-specific amplification. MLP L32 shows extreme activity: -15.43 total proj with top eraser N32:2496 (-1.508 K-proj, +2.061 V-proj) suppressing alternatives while N32:4581 (+1.003 K-proj) supports K.

deep_dives.label: Local context reading L1-L18
deep_dives.caption: Attention heads read the LIFAG[K]QLEDG local sequence to assemble polar surface context. L24 head 19 (2.567 proj, 94.5% local attention) is the strongest local reader, while L16 head 15 (-1.681 proj, 93.6% local) suppresses hydrophobic alternatives.

deep_dives.caption: Early features encode surface-exposed polar character. F9:5728 (50.49 proj, attn) and F18:6632 (21.16 proj, attn) capture the polar environment that projects toward Q/N in the logit lens—this is context assembly, not prediction.

deep_dives.label: MLP transition L23-L25
deep_dives.caption: The perception-to-decision boundary. L23 MLP contributes +2.67 proj (N23:1079 at 0.431 K-proj, N23:2501 at 0.390 K-proj). L24-25 MLPs activate AA-specific prediction neurons: N24:4998 (0.718 K-proj), N25:3067 (0.661 K-proj). Watch K emerge from 1.28% to 9.8%.

deep_dives.label: MLP decision L29-L31
deep_dives.caption: The decisive MLP push for K. N29:1029 (1.265 proj) is the strongest K-specific neuron in the entire network. N31:4836 (1.428 proj) provides massive late amplification. L30 shows conflict: +4.06 MLP proj toward K but -4.42 total as erasers suppress alternatives.

deep_dives.label: Final prediction channels L33
deep_dives.caption: L33 features deliver the final verdict. F33:6423 (124.19 proj, attn) and F33:4166 (119.77 proj, attn) are extremely high-projection K-specific channels. F33:7063 (112.18 proj, MLP) provides complementary support. These are pure prediction features, not context encoders.

deep_dives.label: K vs R competition L28-L32
deep_dives.caption: Track the K/R competition. L28-29: both rise together (R 26.1%, K 25.4%). L30-31: R peaks (35.3%) but K gains ground via N31:4836. L32: K-specific features activate while R-supporting neurons are suppressed. Final: K 87.5%, R 10.8%.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts K by assembling a surface-exposed, functionally constrained context (7 co-evolving positions, minimal structural packing) and activating positive charge prediction channels in L27-33. The decisive evidence is the late MLP surge: N29:1029 (1.265 proj) and N31:4836 (1.428 proj) provide K-specific amplification that R cannot match. Final-layer attention features (F33:6423 at 124.19 proj) seal the victory. The early polar signal (Q, N dominance through L23) reflects context assembly, not misprediction—the model correctly transitions from 'reading polar surface environment' to 'predicting specific positive charge' at the L23-25 boundary.
